    <Folder>
      <name>Intelligence Summary</name>
      <Placemark>
        <name>AI Council Assessment</name>
        <styleUrl>#intel</styleUrl>
        <description>The synthesized intelligence assessment reveals a US military operating at elevated operational tempo across multiple theaters, with a clear emphasis on global force projection, regional deterrence, and counter-narcotics efforts. The Eastern Mediterranean remains a critical flashpoint, with USS Gerald R. Ford maintaining an unprecedented 295+ day deployment, underscoring sustained NATO engagement and regional stability operations. Concurrently, USS Dwight D. Eisenhower’s in-port maintenance in Norfolk following a fire incident highlights both the resilience and vulnerabilities of the carrier fleet, with recovery timelines likely influencing regional tasking. Amphibious ready groups USS America and USS Tripoli in the Western Pacific signal continued Marine Corps expeditionary readiness, while destroyers and cruisers such as USS Zumwalt and USS San Jacinto in the Eastern Pacific support counter-narcotics strikes and maritime security—aligned with recent US Southern Command operations targeting 51 suspected drug boats. High-altitude ISR platforms, including the E-3 Sentry over the eastern Atlantic and RC-26 variants, indicate persistent surveillance over critical chokepoints and potential conflict zones, likely feeding into NATO and regional command-and-control networks. Strategic airlift missions by C-17s and C-32s in Kansas and Crete reflect ongoing global mobility and VIP transport requirements, while rotary-wing assets like MH-60 Seahawks and CH-47 Chinooks conduct SAR, MEDEVAC, and utility operations across CONUS and coastal regions. The data also suggests heightened focus on countering Russian submarine activities in allied EEZs, as evidenced by UK operations and likely US support. Overall, the military posture reflects a dual-track strategy: maintaining forward presence and deterrence in high-tension regions (Middle East, Western Pacific) while sustaining domestic readiness and counter-narcotics operations. Maintenance backlogs, particularly for carriers and destroyers, pose a readiness risk but are being mitigated through phased deployments and in-port recovery. The absence of position data for certain ISR and transport platforms indicates operational security measures, but the breadth of tracked activity suggests a broad, multi-domain surveillance and response capability.</description>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>0,0,0</coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
    </Folder>
